"### Asynchronous Demonstration

```javascript
// Promise.race() executes the first promise to resolve (or reject).
// It's useful when you need the fastest result, even if it's an error.

const promise1 = new Promise((resolve, reject) => setTimeout(() => resolve("Promise 1 resolved"), 1000));
const promise2 = new Promise((resolve, reject) => setTimeout(() => resolve("Promise 2 resolved"), 500));
const promise3 = new Promise((resolve, reject) => setTimeout(() => reject("Promise 3 rejected"), 2000)); //Rejecting promise

Promise.race([promise1, promise2, promise3]) // Race them!
  .then(result => {
    console.log("Winning promise:", result); // Outputs "Promise 2 resolved" because it's the fastest
  })
  .catch(error => {
    console.error("First to reject:", error); // Outputs "First to reject: Promise 3 rejected"
  });
```

**Real-world Scenario (Why Promise.race() over Promise.all()):**

Imagine you're building a web application that needs to fetch data from multiple APIs.  However, one of those APIs is known to be unreliable and frequently returns errors. Using `Promise.all()`, you'd wait for *all* requests to complete – even if one fails, you'll still wait indefinitely.  `Promise.race()` is better in this case. It allows you to define a timeout for each API request. The first API to either resolve or reject (due to a timeout or error) will be the one that determines the overall result.  This prevents your application from getting stuck waiting forever on a failing API and allows you to handle errors more quickly and gracefully.  It's suitable when you want a quick answer or a default fallback when one of the promises fails.



Self-Assessment: 5.0
